1
00:00:01,532 --> 00:00:10,795
For the past few evenings, I've been talking about the Brahma Vihara, the beautiful states of mind and heart expressed when we're in harmony with the world.

2
00:00:11,458 --> 00:00:13,622
The basis is metta or goodwill.

3
00:00:14,185 --> 00:00:19,137
We wish all beings to be happy, but metta doesn't make us smile with delight in all situations.

4
00:00:19,117 --> 00:00:20,079
circumstances.

5
00:00:20,739 --> 00:00:34,728
The intelligence we cultivate in Vipassana is also very much to the fore and we are acutely aware of the ever-present potential for suffering and the need to take care that we don't unwittingly get the wheel turning.

6
00:00:34,709 --> 00:00:45,131
As we learn to acknowledge and bear with our emotions in Vipassana, we are better able to tune into the emotional tone of various situations that we find in our daily lives.

7
00:00:46,052 --> 00:00:53,729
Then we can tailor our goodwill towards compassion, mudita or equanimity so as to fit in with different circumstances.

8
00:00:54,740 --> 00:00:56,762
Suppose you're meeting a friend for coffee.

9
00:00:57,003 --> 00:01:02,029
You're feeling bright and breezy and giving silent good wishes to everyone in the restaurant.

10
00:01:02,729 --> 00:01:07,936
Then you see your friend coming and, to your surprise, you see them looking weary and glum.

11
00:01:08,716 --> 00:01:12,200
The simple meta wish, may you be happy, just doesn't fit.

12
00:01:12,662 --> 00:01:15,745
It doesn't show any sensitivity to the situation.

13
00:01:16,365 --> 00:01:23,834
You might prefer if they'd feel bright and breezy to match your own mood, but that wish is out of kilter with their present reality.

14
00:01:23,814 --> 00:01:31,989
So you have to be prepared to let go of your bright and breezy mood and instead take into consideration that something may be amiss.

15
00:01:33,111 --> 00:01:38,763
As you let your mood change from brightness to concern, your goodwill can take on the hue of compassion.

16
00:01:39,403 --> 00:01:45,114
This more sombre form of goodwill fits when you're aware of witnessing some degree of suffering.

17
00:01:46,057 --> 00:01:53,906
The phrase, may you be free from suffering, acknowledges both the suffering and your friends potential to find freedom.

18
00:01:56,501 --> 00:02:06,218
this good wish while you watch them approach means your tone of voice and body language will express empathy and care for whatever's troubling them.

19
00:02:06,239 --> 00:02:20,383
To take another example, suppose you're walking down a street wishing strangers well as they pass by, but something catches your eye and in a dark alley you see someone squatting on the pavement injecting drugs into a vein.

20
00:02:20,362 --> 00:02:25,473
Again, the straightforward meta-wish, nay you'll be happy, just doesn't work here.

21
00:02:26,134 --> 00:02:32,668
It would be glossing over the reality, refusing to engage with the human tragedy you're witnessing.

22
00:02:33,239 --> 00:02:42,567
The wish may you be free from suffering fits better as this is certainly a situation of suffering and it's possible that the person is suffering very deeply.

23
00:02:43,247 --> 00:02:51,455
But it doesn't acknowledge the kernel of the problem that as far as we can judge the person is making things worse for themselves by drug addiction.

24
00:02:52,896 --> 00:02:59,402
Equanimity is the Brahma Vihara which allows us to cope with what we don't want and judge as wrong.

25
00:03:00,282 --> 00:03:03,246
It accommodates both good and evil.

26
00:03:03,225 --> 00:03:12,645
The understanding of karma provides a channel for equanimous good wishes, such as, may you be able to bear with the karma you are creating.

27
00:03:13,728 --> 00:03:20,121
Or it could help to phrase the wish in more mundane terms, such as, may you stop harming yourself.

28
00:03:20,100 --> 00:03:24,147
Or may you learn to cope with your challenges more skillfully?

29
00:03:25,830 --> 00:03:35,747
Now let's say you've made your good wishes for the person shooting drugs and have recovered your good humour and are back to wishing well to strangers as you pass them by.

30
00:03:35,727 --> 00:03:40,373
Then you spy a couple with their arms around one another, obviously deeply in love.

31
00:03:41,115 --> 00:03:47,304
Once again, the metal wish, may you be happy, doesn't fit as they're already so obviously happy.

32
00:03:47,944 --> 00:03:50,207
So they don't need your good wishes on that account.

33
00:03:50,868 --> 00:03:57,498
In this case, you need to form your good wishes in a way that acknowledges and honours their existing happiness.

34
00:03:58,913 --> 00:04:05,500
brings us to mudita or appreciative joy which is the Brahma vihara I want to talk about tonight.

35
00:04:06,281 --> 00:04:13,628
Mudita tunes into our natural human capacity for joy and gives us a skillful way to build on that.

36
00:04:14,711 --> 00:04:23,199
The classic phrase to cultivate mudita is may your happiness continue, may your happiness increase.

37
00:04:26,555 --> 00:04:33,783
If your Mudita channels are open you'll be delighted for them and get a little shot of joy yourself into the bargain.

38
00:04:34,764 --> 00:04:41,814
And as you pass them by and continue wishing well to those all around your good wishes will have an extra animation.

39
00:04:42,514 --> 00:04:45,117
With Mudita happiness is multiplied.

40
00:04:45,158 --> 00:04:48,882
The happiness of the couple became your happiness.

41
00:04:49,927 --> 00:04:53,713
Mudita is all about appreciating the good things in life.

42
00:04:54,394 --> 00:05:01,786
Buddhism tends to have a bad reputation in this department because of the emphasis on the first noble truth of Dukkha.

43
00:05:02,786 --> 00:05:05,612
But joy is also very much part of the Dhamma.

44
00:05:06,353 --> 00:05:12,221
It will certainly be there when we're fully developed, as described in this verse from the Dhamma book.

45
00:05:15,187 --> 00:05:18,317
Happy indeed we live, we who possess nothing.

46
00:05:19,238 --> 00:05:23,690
Feeders on joy we shall be, like the radiant gods.

47
00:05:25,235 --> 00:05:28,725
But joy isn't only when we've reached such an exalted state.

48
00:05:31,894 --> 00:05:45,540
After spending years doing mortification practices and deciding they led nowhere, the Buddha then remembered his joyful experience as a child under the rose apple tree watching his father ploughing.

49
00:05:46,622 --> 00:05:53,514
The mortification practices had dismissed joy as worthless but now the Buddha questioned himself on this.

50
00:05:54,000 --> 00:06:03,110
He realised the joy he had experienced wasn't to do with attachment to the world but was what he described as a blameless joy.

51
00:06:03,151 --> 00:06:10,499
He decided he'd no longer dismiss that and instead would actively cultivate it as an aid to meditation.

52
00:06:11,439 --> 00:06:14,762
Thus we have joy as a factor of enlightenment.

53
00:06:16,865 --> 00:06:19,468
The Pali term for this is pity.

54
00:06:19,903 --> 00:06:24,189
In this case, joy emerges from fascination with the pursuit of truth.

55
00:06:24,810 --> 00:06:28,053
We're glad to be seeking out and sensing the path to freedom.

56
00:06:28,814 --> 00:06:33,040
It's not linked to anything specific in life, like seeing a couple in love.

57
00:06:33,701 --> 00:06:38,487
Mudita, on the other hand, arises when we are touched by the beauty of life.

58
00:06:39,028 --> 00:06:42,892
Young love, the birth of a baby, the smile of a friend.

59
00:06:43,574 --> 00:06:46,958
It's the response of gladness to the good things in life.

60
00:06:49,098 --> 00:06:50,781
It can be a bit confusing.

61
00:06:51,302 --> 00:06:56,072
In meditation we rejoice in freedom, letting go of our attachments in life.

62
00:06:56,713 --> 00:06:59,059
In mudita we rejoice in life itself.

63
00:06:59,821 --> 00:07:01,144
Is there not a contradiction?

64
00:07:02,485 --> 00:07:04,170
To embrace both sources of

65
00:07:07,728 --> 00:07:09,591
part of our path to freedom.

66
00:07:10,372 --> 00:07:14,817
For example we need families to help us through infancy and childhood.

67
00:07:15,458 --> 00:07:20,125
We need some level of education to be able to hear and understand the Dhamma.

68
00:07:20,886 --> 00:07:27,795
We need a stable society to give us the possibility of retreat centers where we can practice meditation.

69
00:07:28,264 --> 00:07:40,940
And of course we need food, clean air, water, medicine to keep us alive until our moment of enlightenment when we fully understand that which goes beyond life and death.

70
00:07:41,949 --> 00:07:52,225
Although freedom, nibbana, is not dependent on education or families or a stable society, we can only find our path to freedom in the midst of all these.

71
00:07:53,028 --> 00:08:01,420
At one level, mudita can be seen as a thank you to all the conditions that allow for ourselves and others to tread the path to freedom.

72
00:08:02,783 --> 00:08:05,406
Mudita builds on our natural joie de vivre.

73
00:08:06,067 --> 00:08:09,814
As babies, we took delight in seeing faces we recognised.

74
00:08:10,148 --> 00:08:17,339
playing with whoever and whatever came our way, in food and comfort and being able to explore and learn and so on.

75
00:08:18,451 --> 00:08:27,223
This delight only led to Dukkha because of attachment, the mistake of believing we could control and own all the lovely stuff.

76
00:08:27,244 --> 00:08:35,917
But the delight itself animated us, let us develop confidence and trust, help to smile and make connections and learn to communicate.

77
00:08:36,717 --> 00:08:46,111
Mudita cultivates delight with all its benefits for our psyche and perhaps also for our bodies without the delusion of attachment.

78
00:08:47,071 --> 00:08:55,207
Our baby's capacity for delight is still there, even though it might by now seem buried under tons of depression and anxiety.

79
00:08:56,090 --> 00:09:04,707
To recapture our joie de vivre, we need to reflect on what really nurtures us and make a deliberate attempt to appreciate all these.

80
00:09:05,937 --> 00:09:12,508
The Mahamangala Sutta, which we chant last thing at night, gives the Buddha's list of things we can rejoice in.

81
00:09:13,229 --> 00:09:18,677
He places associating with wise companions first among the list of great blessings.

82
00:09:19,639 --> 00:09:22,325
If you have a meditation group, you're really lucky.

83
00:09:22,905 --> 00:09:31,539
Not only does it get you onto the cushion regularly, it also gives you the chance to discuss the Dharma and how it applies to the many challenges in life.

84
00:09:32,768 --> 00:09:36,851
Trying to put our understanding into words really helps it sharpen.

85
00:09:37,493 --> 00:09:44,620
It can be uncomfortable as we only notice all our confusions when we try to put our vague notions into a string of words.

86
00:09:45,541 --> 00:09:49,806
But every attempt is worthwhile for both you and your friends.

87
00:09:50,366 --> 00:09:59,316
Together you can help each other sort through some of the confusions and let each person's unique perspective become part of the group wisdom.

88
00:09:59,886 --> 00:10:01,073
Try making the wish.

89
00:10:01,596 --> 00:10:03,407
May our happiness continue.

90
00:10:03,909 --> 00:10:05,418
May our happiness increase.

91
00:10:05,961 --> 00:10:07,450
Whenever you meet up with your group.

92
00:10:09,673 --> 00:10:17,183
The next on the list is residing in a suitable place, meaning somewhere that encourages and supports us in our practice.

93
00:10:17,904 --> 00:10:20,028
So certainly Satipanya fits the bill.

94
00:10:20,649 --> 00:10:24,794
But your own home can be conducive to meditation practice too.

95
00:10:25,495 --> 00:10:30,702
For some people, making a small shrine helps or setting aside a room for meditation.

96
00:10:31,443 --> 00:10:35,549
For me, the main thing has been to establish the habit of a daily practice.

97
00:10:36,149 --> 00:10:39,495
Over the years, this became more and more central to my life

98
00:10:39,761 --> 00:10:41,465
deep source of refuge.

99
00:10:42,326 --> 00:10:54,090
After a challenging day at work it was such a relief to know that in the evening I could close the door behind me and let meditation clean out the layer of fractious energy that had built up over the day.

100
00:10:54,149 --> 00:10:59,559
So if we're lucky enough to have a home we have a deep reason to rejoice.

101
00:10:59,945 --> 00:11:10,495
Caring for our home, keeping it clean and tidy, and adding touches of beauty are also part of mudita practice, a way of saying thank you for this precious gift.

102
00:11:11,357 --> 00:11:12,942
Beauty might seem unnecessary,

103
00:11:13,427 --> 00:11:18,594
After all, we're cultivating equanimity, so why should we care whether things are drab or pretty?

104
00:11:19,514 --> 00:11:24,360
But that line of thinking is drawing us towards indifference rather than equanimity.

105
00:11:24,961 --> 00:11:33,971
It encourages a don't care, doesn't matter attitude to the world, whereas true equanimity only exists within a deep care for the world.

106
00:11:34,831 --> 00:11:38,135
Beautifying our surroundings is a way to express that care.

107
00:11:38,755 --> 00:11:42,860
It also shows sensitivity to the way the human body and psyche

108
00:11:42,841 --> 00:11:44,124
Thrive on pleasure.

109
00:11:45,267 --> 00:11:50,919
The feelings we recognise as pleasant vedana have a soothing effect on our bodies and mind.

110
00:11:51,822 --> 00:11:55,912
I imagine various hormones are released to calm our nervous systems.

111
00:11:56,553 --> 00:12:00,562
Why not give ourselves every opportunity for such benefits?

112
00:12:01,909 --> 00:12:03,851
The Buddha appreciated beauty.

113
00:12:04,552 --> 00:12:12,162
In the Parinibbana Sutta, which tracks the last stages of his life, we find him wandering from one shrine to another.

114
00:12:12,962 --> 00:12:18,089
Along the way, he says to Ananda, Come, Ananda, let us go to Vesali.

115
00:12:18,950 --> 00:12:20,871
Pleasant, Ananda, is Vesali.

116
00:12:21,653 --> 00:12:30,043
Pleasant are the shrines of Udena, Gotamaka, Satambaka, Bahuputa, Sarandada and Kapala.

117
00:12:31,272 --> 00:12:39,424
In fact, he repeats this a number of times as he moves from shrine to shrine, as if the memory of their beauty meant a lot to him.

118
00:12:40,365 --> 00:12:50,381
You can imagine the effort it would have taken for a dying man of 80 years to walk from place to place, and yet this is how he spent his last days.

119
00:12:51,783 --> 00:12:58,173
The way he kept repeating the list of beautiful shrines suggests their memory gave him energy for the journey.

120
00:12:59,234 --> 00:13:05,621
We can take this as encouragement to adorn our homes and whatever we value as supporting us in life.

121
00:13:07,303 --> 00:13:12,591
And of course our home wouldn't exist if it weren't for all the supporting social structures around.

122
00:13:13,091 --> 00:13:22,423
Roads, shops, sewage pipes and electricity, as well as courts of law that uphold our right to lock the door behind us and meditate.

123
00:13:22,774 --> 00:13:33,447
Every aspect of the society we live in contributes something to the fact that we have time and space to practice, Dhamma books to read, Dhamma talks to listen to.

124
00:13:33,488 --> 00:13:40,255
Think of the enormous web of conditions that allowed Buddhist teachings reach our Western ears.

125
00:13:41,057 --> 00:13:49,947
Seeing things this way, any contribution we make towards society can be done in the spirit of mudita.

126
00:13:50,416 --> 00:13:55,111
Say the water pressure drops and we have to get onto the local council to get it sorted.

127
00:13:55,874 --> 00:13:58,482
Generally, we think of this as a real pain in the neck.

128
00:13:59,044 --> 00:14:02,316
But just think of what a gift it is to have fresh water on tap.

129
00:14:02,953 --> 00:14:09,121
It was my mother's 90th birthday recently, and as part of this, she decided to write up the story of her life.

130
00:14:09,962 --> 00:14:15,730
When she was young, the family water had to be drawn from a spring in a boggy field a good distance from the house.

131
00:14:16,691 --> 00:14:24,000
And if you wanted it heated, it was a question of lighting the fire and pouring the buckets of water into a cauldron for a few hours.

132
00:14:25,364 --> 00:14:32,078
reflecting on how much letter time we get because of not having to walk miles to collect water from a well each day.

133
00:14:32,099 --> 00:14:36,269
This might bring a sense of gratitude into our dealings with the council.

134
00:14:37,009 --> 00:14:42,562
We might even take little jots of hope and joy away with us every time we get a helpful response.

135
00:14:43,706 --> 00:14:56,083
Now of course you could argue that rejoicing in your local council and your home and meditation group is only going to lead to dukkha when these go the way of all earthly phenomena and eventually fall apart.

136
00:14:56,904 --> 00:15:01,211
That line of thinking represents fear of attachment, not wisdom.

137
00:15:02,052 --> 00:15:11,706
Our problem is that we're already deeply attached to our possessions, friends, activities, as well as to our social status as householders.

138
00:15:11,686 --> 00:15:14,711
and therefore deserving of running water in our taps.

139
00:15:15,493 --> 00:15:19,240
Deciding not to rejoice in these won't help matters at all.

140
00:15:19,279 --> 00:15:27,355
We only learn the art of non-attachment by experiencing the pain that comes when these things fall apart.

141
00:15:27,375 --> 00:15:34,268
So we might as well go through that pain for the sake of worthy attachments, like all those the Buddha suggests.

142
00:15:34,822 --> 00:15:42,190
And, as we get more and more involved in the meditation group, we'll find our buttons being pushed left, right and centre.

143
00:15:42,870 --> 00:15:54,063
All this shows us our attachment to personality styles, ideas of how the group should be run, interpretations of the Dharma, preferences for meditation techniques and so on.

144
00:15:55,024 --> 00:16:01,032
If we didn't put any effort into bonding with the group, we could just float in and out of the meetings,

145
00:16:01,147 --> 00:16:08,535
congratulating ourselves on our equanimity and raising our eyes to heaven when we hear squabbles among the more established members.

146
00:16:09,596 --> 00:16:12,740
But this is to mistake indifference for equanimity.

147
00:16:13,360 --> 00:16:24,734
We only learn true equanimity by putting our heart into our activities, making deep connections and bearing with any reactionary pain as part of our learning curve.

148
00:16:25,575 --> 00:16:30,681
Mudita helps us open our hearts to form those essential connections.

149
00:16:31,859 --> 00:16:36,581
Next on the Buddha's list is the joy at having done meritorious actions.

150
00:16:37,306 --> 00:16:39,979
We easily miss this source of mudita.

151
00:16:40,499 --> 00:16:44,687
Say, for example, we help an elderly person cross the road.

152
00:16:45,227 --> 00:16:50,499
It would be very easy to dismiss this with words like, that was nothing, anyone would have done the same thing.

153
00:16:51,279 --> 00:16:55,388
But according to the Buddha, we are to rejoice at every good deed.

154
00:16:55,869 --> 00:17:02,000
We need to say well done to ourselves for any small act of kindness or generosity.

155
00:17:02,825 --> 00:17:06,369
I found this really helped with my recovery from laryngectomy.

156
00:17:07,030 --> 00:17:16,665
I couldn't find any joy in my new state until it occurred to me to think of my role in life as someone who cared for a laryngectomy.

157
00:17:18,087 --> 00:17:25,018
I started to see every little thing I had to do, cleaning the various tubes, taking medicine, doing exercises.

158
00:17:25,690 --> 00:17:29,578
acts of kindness for someone who had suffered laryngectomy.

159
00:17:30,441 --> 00:17:35,713
This gave me a new source of joy, and with that my self-confidence started to recover.

160
00:17:36,315 --> 00:17:41,708
And when I recovered enough to be able to do a few things for others, these really meant a lot.

161
00:17:41,688 --> 00:17:46,558
It might just have been that I cut the veg for dinner or sorted through the recycling bins.

162
00:17:47,280 --> 00:17:59,088
Before the illness I wouldn't have paid much heed to these but after a long spell of being totally dependent I saw how much joy I was on offer from being able to play a role in society.

163
00:18:00,232 --> 00:18:05,380
Now of course we can get attached to our roles and get very uptight when we're not appreciated.

164
00:18:06,040 --> 00:18:15,073
But if we keep reminding ourselves that our motivation is kindness and congratulating ourselves for that kindness, this undercuts the attachment.

165
00:18:16,134 --> 00:18:18,436
Reflecting on the law of kamma helps with this.

166
00:18:19,097 --> 00:18:24,645
We shape our future happiness or unhappiness depending on the motivation for our actions.

167
00:18:25,567 --> 00:18:29,531
Acting out of kindness sows seeds for future happiness.

168
00:18:29,511 --> 00:18:33,739
acting out of anger or meanness, sow seeds of unhappiness.

169
00:18:34,640 --> 00:18:37,384
Karma is our only real possession in life.

170
00:18:37,925 --> 00:18:39,848
Everything else will fall apart in time.

171
00:18:40,609 --> 00:18:45,598
So we're looking after our future self really well when we do things out of kindness.

172
00:18:46,319 --> 00:18:50,727
And we can definitely congratulate ourselves for every good deed.

173
00:18:51,989 --> 00:19:00,000
Further on in the Mangala Sutta, the Buddha includes supporting our families as a blessing in which to rejoice.

174
00:19:00,701 --> 00:19:02,805
There's so much involved in family life.

175
00:19:03,425 --> 00:19:09,414
All the daily chores of cooking and cleaning, educating children, caring for older parents.

176
00:19:10,155 --> 00:19:13,119
Can we make a practice of joy out of all this?

177
00:19:13,538 --> 00:19:20,028
For that, we have to spend quality time with our family, rather than let it all become a burden of hard work.

178
00:19:20,769 --> 00:19:33,268
Eating together is one way of expressing value for one another, and activities like sports, playing cards, scrabble, crosswords, going for walks, whatever pastimes your family enjoys.

179
00:19:34,295 --> 00:19:39,109
If we're not careful, TV can be a mind-numbing escape from interaction.

180
00:19:39,731 --> 00:19:45,991
But we can also make it a focus for shared enjoyment, chatting about the programme like they do on Gogglebox.

181
00:19:46,646 --> 00:19:51,054
Remember, kama is about motivation, not the activity itself.

182
00:19:51,714 --> 00:19:58,506
If our motivation for watching TV is to have some relaxing and enjoyable time with our family, we're on the right track.

183
00:19:59,067 --> 00:20:03,974
To help with this, we can inject little mudita wishes every now and again.

184
00:20:04,015 --> 00:20:06,198
May our happiness continue.

185
00:20:06,558 --> 00:20:08,402
May our happiness increase.

186
00:20:09,461 --> 00:20:14,549
Having said that, we have to take care that our activities don't violate the precepts.

187
00:20:15,151 --> 00:20:23,163
We can't justify watching pornography or sadism by saying, may my happiness continue, may my happiness increase.

188
00:20:23,943 --> 00:20:34,760
So we have to choose forms of entertainment which stimulate wonder, for example, or humour, or understanding of human nature, or appreciation of skill, and so on.

189
00:20:35,955 --> 00:20:42,525
So the Buddha isn't asking us to neglect our families, homes or society for the sake of enlightenment.

190
00:20:43,066 --> 00:20:57,306
Instead, we bring all these within the definition of what is our path, by appreciating them and adding to their beauty or joy wherever possible, while we remind ourselves that they cannot be relied upon for lasting happiness.

191
00:20:58,298 --> 00:21:10,319
So we can't find any number of occasions for mudita, but it can be quite a challenge because earthly joys don't last forever and because we can't own them or control them to any meaningful degree.

192
00:21:11,221 --> 00:21:12,825
It can be quite poignant.

193
00:21:13,566 --> 00:21:16,892
This is why mudita can be quite a challenging brahma vihara.

194
00:21:17,753 --> 00:21:21,099
I sometimes find myself preferring funerals to weddings, for example.

195
00:21:21,079 --> 00:21:33,676
For example, there is some comfort in knowing it's okay to feel and express sorrow, whereas there can be a confusing disconnect when sadness is felt but it's not the appropriate emotion to express.

196
00:21:34,438 --> 00:21:41,146
At a wedding, for example, if we're feeling depressed, the effort to keep smiling and making small talk can be quite wearying.

197
00:21:41,988 --> 00:21:48,295
The ephemeral nature of joy means that like all phenomena, it fades away moment after moment.

198
00:21:49,016 --> 00:21:58,428
Unless we have a background level of peace within ourselves, the experience of joy fading away can be so hard to bear that we find ways of excluding it altogether.

199
00:21:59,269 --> 00:22:09,800
This process underlies the far enemies of mudita, which centre around jealousy for other people's happiness and disparaging our own sources of happiness.

200
00:22:11,198 --> 00:22:15,726
Many myths and legends illustrate the destructive power of jealousy.

201
00:22:16,426 --> 00:22:25,782
In the Bible we have the first record of murder when Cain killed his brother Abel out of jealousy for the favour God showed to Abel.

202
00:22:26,364 --> 00:22:36,160
And a bit later, Joseph is set upon by all ten of his elder brothers who are jealous of the love their father showers on his younger son.

203
00:22:36,140 --> 00:22:43,787
And Snow White, remember, was cast out of the palace by the jealous queen who couldn't bear to be judged less beautiful than her daughter.

204
00:22:45,469 --> 00:22:51,134
All these stories go on to illustrate how jealousy destroys the one who harbours it.

205
00:22:51,894 --> 00:23:03,025
Cain becoming an outcast, Joseph's brother suffering famine and imprisonment and the wicked queen having to dance herself to death in red hot slippers at Snow White's wedding.

206
00:23:03,967 --> 00:23:13,455
Shakespeare gives a graphic illustration of the self-destructive power of jealousy when Iago warns Othello, O beware, my lord, of jealousy.

207
00:23:13,896 --> 00:23:17,681
It is the green-eyed monster which does mock the meat it feeds on.

208
00:23:19,281 --> 00:23:29,011
These epic stories show jealousy in the form of murderous rage, but its power can also drive the drip-drip destructiveness of peevishness squandered

209
00:23:31,117 --> 00:23:35,587
In fear of their success, we denigrate our rival's achievement as worthless.

210
00:23:36,249 --> 00:23:45,229
Caught up in the thralls of jealousy, their success implies our failure and the only way to relieve our pain is to belittle their achievement.

211
00:23:46,204 --> 00:23:55,127
To the extent that we're identified with our skills and talents, we're in danger of jealousy when another exhibits a similar talent.

212
00:23:55,789 --> 00:24:02,948
If you read Little Women, you'll remember the night Amy burned her sister Jo's precious manuscript in a fit of jealousy.

213
00:24:02,928 --> 00:24:16,821
The 1950 Nobel Prize was said to have been offered to Thomas Edison and Nikola Tesla for their work in electromagnetism, but they both refused to accept it if the other person was to be included.

214
00:24:17,782 --> 00:24:24,230
Jealousy can destroy any partnership, be it artistic, scientific, business or even religious.

215
00:24:25,151 --> 00:24:28,934
Deva Dutta's attempt to kill the Buddha being a prime example.

216
00:24:30,603 --> 00:24:33,406
Jealousy also ruins personal relationships.

217
00:24:34,087 --> 00:24:37,251
We want our partner to be totally bound up in us.

218
00:24:37,271 --> 00:24:41,258
If they enjoy someone else's company, we take it as betrayal.

219
00:24:41,897 --> 00:24:46,724
And of course, if they leave us for another, we're in an agony of hatred for both parties.

220
00:24:47,846 --> 00:24:52,353
Practicing mudita for ourselves is a powerful antidote to jealousy.

221
00:24:53,054 --> 00:24:59,142
We build self-confidence by appreciating ourselves and especially every effort we make.

222
00:24:59,813 --> 00:25:01,636
good karma for ourselves.

223
00:25:03,019 --> 00:25:08,790
As we build our own sense of self-worth, we're less threatened by the talents or good fortune of others.

224
00:25:10,292 --> 00:25:13,941
Congratulating ourselves is in itself an exercise in mudita.

225
00:25:14,260 --> 00:25:15,222
It stirs joy.

226
00:25:16,654 --> 00:25:18,659
healthy sense of ourselves is worthwhile.

227
00:25:19,560 --> 00:25:23,106
We need this healthy sense of self to sustain us on the path.

228
00:25:23,769 --> 00:25:29,880
Sometimes we mistake the teaching on anatta, not self, to mean that we shouldn't have any sense of self.

229
00:25:30,520 --> 00:25:33,988
So whenever we feel a sense of self, we condemn ourselves saying,

230
00:25:33,968 --> 00:25:52,467
i shouldn't feel like this or i shouldn't be here but the buddha often uses the word self in a very positive way for example he says that if we truly care for ourselves we will practice the dharma let's face it the teaching on anatta can be very confusing

231
00:25:53,019 --> 00:26:02,775
I like Bhikkhu Thanissaro's interpretation that sometimes the sense of self is appropriate and helps us along the path and other times it leads to suffering.

232
00:26:03,615 --> 00:26:20,142
Our job is to get better and better at recognising whether we should let our sense of self help us do what we need to do or whether it's one of those times when the sense of self is curling itself around some habit based on greed, aversion or delusion

233
00:26:20,122 --> 00:26:22,970
In which case, of course, we need to let it go.

234
00:26:24,294 --> 00:26:32,477
When our judgment tells us that what we're doing is wise, we strengthen the sense of self needed to follow through on the activity.

235
00:26:33,048 --> 00:26:44,443
But when we've done the activity and the self wants to do it again, and again for no good reason, then it's time to accept the truth of anatta and let that sense of self dissolve.

236
00:26:45,585 --> 00:26:49,210
So the self is something to care for, according to the Buddha.

237
00:26:49,770 --> 00:26:55,298
The only thing we have to worry about is making the mistake of expecting it to give us permanent happiness.

238
00:26:56,099 --> 00:27:01,586
Like everything else in this phenomenal universe, it is temporary and contingent.

239
00:27:02,156 --> 00:27:10,767
But of all the temporary contingent entities we find here, the self is the most important, the one we must cherish most deeply.

240
00:27:11,589 --> 00:27:15,133
To practice the Dhamma is to care deeply for ourself.

241
00:27:15,814 --> 00:27:21,538
We give ourselves the gift of mindfulness moment after moment, asking nothing in return.

242
00:27:22,279 --> 00:27:25,403
As you all know, this is a tough challenge.

243
00:27:25,423 --> 00:27:37,934
We fortify ourselves for this challenge by appreciating every good deed we do, thanking ourselves for every effort we've made to practice, congratulating ourselves for everything we do well.

244
00:27:37,914 --> 00:27:42,644
This is strengthening the sense of self that does wise actions.

245
00:27:43,346 --> 00:27:50,922
Just as an ideal parent would praise and encourage their child, we must do the same for our poor, downtrodden selves.

246
00:27:51,943 --> 00:27:58,017
Denigration is less dramatic than jealousy, but also powerfully destructive.

247
00:27:57,997 --> 00:28:02,040
In fact, it's such a quiet form of negativity, we hardly notice it.

248
00:28:02,682 --> 00:28:07,046
What's happening is that we see the joy is too little to bother appreciating.

249
00:28:07,645 --> 00:28:14,512
So we disparage our incredibly good fortune of living in a peaceful society, having shelter and enough to eat.

250
00:28:15,453 --> 00:28:21,900
We rarely remember to be grateful for the gift of the Dhamma or having friends to practice with.

251
00:28:21,920 --> 00:28:24,982
We only appreciate our health when it's gone.

252
00:28:26,481 --> 00:28:29,045
Denigration also destroys relationships.

253
00:28:29,566 --> 00:28:33,490
Belittling a child or partner is a powerful form of bullying.

254
00:28:34,011 --> 00:28:35,773
It keeps the other from flourishing.

255
00:28:36,515 --> 00:28:39,618
The belittled party comes to believe their worthlessness.

256
00:28:40,099 --> 00:28:42,083
Their personality and talents wither.

257
00:28:43,044 --> 00:28:51,595
Lucy illustrated this perfectly in a Peanuts comic strip, saying, ''The trouble with you, Charlie Brown, is that you're you.''

258
00:28:52,199 --> 00:29:06,625
Apart from the interpersonal level, we regularly extend our disparaging remarks to collective aspects of human endeavour, remembering only the failures of institutions, politicians, technology and society.

259
00:29:07,326 --> 00:29:13,616
This bespeaks bitterness, resulting from our repeated attempts to shut joy out of our hearts.

260
00:29:14,473 --> 00:29:19,060
For some strange reason, we're often encouraged culturally to denigrate ourselves.

261
00:29:19,622 --> 00:29:20,502
I'm no good at this.

262
00:29:21,344 --> 00:29:23,267
I always make a mess of things.

263
00:29:23,968 --> 00:29:25,691
I can't ever get things right.

264
00:29:26,432 --> 00:29:31,420
In one sense, it's a form of appeasement, a way of saying I'm not a threat to you.

265
00:29:32,101 --> 00:29:34,203
It defines us as one of the gang.

266
00:29:34,183 --> 00:29:39,433
If we see it in that playful way, just a form of social pleasantry, then it's not harmful.

267
00:29:39,894 --> 00:29:43,862
But to the extent that we're really convinced of it, we're damaging ourselves.

268
00:29:44,843 --> 00:29:52,917
None of us would like to be thought of as a bully, and yet the self-disparaging remarks we make to ourselves are actually those of a bully.

269
00:29:53,000 --> 00:30:03,794
We are shaming ourselves rather than seeing the liberating truth of Anatta, that I cannot be expected to get everything right because conditions are always beyond my control.

270
00:30:03,834 --> 00:30:16,289
We can start to undo the habit of self-denigration by practising mudita for ourselves, saying, well done, even just for putting on our shoes, mindfully of course.

271
00:30:17,721 --> 00:30:21,228
The near enemy of mudita is excitement and excess.

272
00:30:22,069 --> 00:30:29,742
It's natural to get excited when there's something to celebrate, but indulging this only brings the inevitable downer when the party's over.

273
00:30:30,545 --> 00:30:33,569
Think of the excess around Christmas and weddings.

274
00:30:33,549 --> 00:30:48,471
same for other supposedly religious celebrations in ireland many families go into huge debt over first communion outfits for example even when we invite a friend to tea we can go over the top in preparations

275
00:30:49,260 --> 00:30:54,307
We must take the daft excess for mudita because we're so happy about the celebration.

276
00:30:55,048 --> 00:30:57,412
But the joy goes to our head and escalates.

277
00:30:58,012 --> 00:31:02,699
In this heady exuberance we lose all sense of proportion.

278
00:31:03,240 --> 00:31:06,683
And in the frenetic excitement things can go badly wrong.

279
00:31:07,384 --> 00:31:13,192
Rivalries flare on matters of style and taste and who should sit where.

280
00:31:13,173 --> 00:31:17,337
For all these reasons, celebrations can be more stressful than happy.

281
00:31:17,858 --> 00:31:21,083
Excessive exuberances turn sour very easily.

282
00:31:21,702 --> 00:31:24,086
Think of the riots that can follow football matches.

283
00:31:24,886 --> 00:31:30,253
I know one sister who hasn't spoken with her brother since an incident at her daughter's christening.

284
00:31:31,736 --> 00:31:39,585
In some forms of illness such as bipolar depression, the high set up by the celebration can lead to depression afterwards.

285
00:31:40,105 --> 00:31:47,854
The far enemies of jealousy and denigration shut out joy, while the near enemies of excitement and excess cling to it.

286
00:31:48,515 --> 00:31:59,647
For Mudita, we need to find the middle way, opening our hearts to the good things in life, while also relaxing, taking it easy, not building things out of proportion.

287
00:32:00,568 --> 00:32:01,509
It's a tightrope.

288
00:32:02,310 --> 00:32:09,640
One moment we're singing someone's praises, next we've exhausted all our goodwill and we're hoping they'll get their comeuppance.

289
00:32:09,906 --> 00:32:16,148
Just being aware which side of the tightrope we've fallen off tells us what needs to be cultivated just now.

290
00:32:17,755 --> 00:32:21,267
In formal meditation, we start off by thinking of someone

291
00:32:23,930 --> 00:32:28,355
For example, become a parent or grandparent, got a new job, won a prize.

292
00:32:29,135 --> 00:32:32,319
We then wish that their happiness will continue and increase.

293
00:32:33,080 --> 00:32:38,268
One variant on the classic phrase that I like is, I'm happy that you're happy.

294
00:32:39,148 --> 00:32:40,510
Usually makes me feel happy.

295
00:32:41,632 --> 00:32:44,115
You could also try a simple well done.

296
00:32:44,415 --> 00:32:47,361
Or in some cases, thank you might fit the bill.

297
00:32:48,303 --> 00:32:53,351
Use whatever phrase best sustains your sense of appreciation when you think of that person.

298
00:32:53,912 --> 00:32:56,777
It doesn't matter if you can't think of a reason for celebration.

299
00:32:57,397 --> 00:33:01,265
Imagine them smiling at a joke or enjoying a book or having coffee with a friend.

300
00:33:01,965 --> 00:33:05,833
The simplest daily jobs can form the basis for no detail.

301
00:33:06,978 --> 00:33:11,865
As with all the Brahma Vihara, the self can be a particularly challenging category.

302
00:33:12,486 --> 00:33:25,726
Remember that any way that your life is going well, family, professional, social, hobbies, physical fitness, meditation practice, has taken hard work and commitment and deserves appreciation.

303
00:33:26,567 --> 00:33:29,411
Sometimes a very simple image works best for me.

304
00:33:29,451 --> 00:33:36,781
I picture myself petting the dog or scattering breadcrumbs for the birds and I say, well done.

305
00:33:39,866 --> 00:33:45,298
If, when you offer mudita to yourself, you feel vanity surface, just note this.

306
00:33:45,920 --> 00:33:49,106
We need to learn to take a healthy pride in our achievements.

307
00:33:49,848 --> 00:33:53,978
Once we're mindful of vanity, it won't spiral into self-delusion.

308
00:33:54,430 --> 00:34:03,208
Similarly, if you feel yourself contracting in jealousy or heady with excitement, just note these, set them aside and continue.

309
00:34:03,849 --> 00:34:09,320
Take a few breaths between good wishes to help you keep a balance and perspective.

310
00:34:09,340 --> 00:34:14,952
If jealousy becomes overpowering, try turning attention to your own successes instead.

311
00:34:14,932 --> 00:34:17,898
murmuring well done to yourself for these.

312
00:34:18,900 --> 00:34:37,514
An alternative that I often find helpful is to encompass the jealousy within a good wish such as a competition between us bring out the best in us both or if the jealousy is about a personal relationship I've used the wish may your love for others help me to love them too.

313
00:34:38,608 --> 00:34:52,416
And as usual, if the near or far enemies or any other hindrances get so overwhelming that none of the remedies works, take a vipassana break and only return to mudita when you feel more balanced.

314
00:34:53,407 --> 00:34:58,936
I want to finish off with a few words about working with the near and far enemies in daily life.

315
00:34:59,998 --> 00:35:06,967
For example, we easily get overexcited about celebrations, especially if we're involved in the planning stage.

316
00:35:07,728 --> 00:35:10,793
Noting this is the first and at times the hardest step.

317
00:35:11,414 --> 00:35:16,782
We can be so caught up in our plans that we forget to be any way mindful.

318
00:35:16,762 --> 00:35:18,045
They just take us over.

319
00:35:18,887 --> 00:35:22,777
Sooner or later, we'll notice that we're going over the top.

320
00:35:22,798 --> 00:35:25,545
Then we have to find strategies to calm ourselves.

321
00:35:26,266 --> 00:35:33,085
Mindful breaths, mindful footsteps, mindful actions, all these help.

322
00:35:33,065 --> 00:35:36,550
Also, take a moment to think of the event you're celebrating.

323
00:35:37,271 --> 00:35:41,097
Ironically, we easily forget this in the midst of all the fussing.

324
00:35:41,617 --> 00:35:47,286
If it's a birthday party, take a moment to bring the person to mind and wish them a happy birthday.

325
00:35:47,947 --> 00:35:51,512
Very often, this brings us back down to earth for a while.

326
00:35:52,387 --> 00:35:56,255
Often we fuss about the arrangements because we want to impress people.

327
00:35:56,817 --> 00:36:09,483
If you think that that could be the case, take time for some self-directed goodwitters as a means of bolstering a healthy sense of your own value and protecting you from going into great excess.

328
00:36:09,463 --> 00:36:18,277
While excitement shows particularly during the planning stage, the far enemies tend to show up during or in the aftermath of the celebration.

329
00:36:19,018 --> 00:36:22,983
As host, we might feel peeved that people aren't more appreciative.

330
00:36:23,244 --> 00:36:28,632
As guest, we might be fed up pretending we're happy.

331
00:36:29,132 --> 00:36:33,699
And as the door closes, both parties may be thinking, thank God that's over.

332
00:36:34,338 --> 00:36:35,800
Celebration isn't easy.

333
00:36:36,420 --> 00:36:39,744
Often problems come about because we feel we ought to be happy.

334
00:36:40,606 --> 00:36:45,733
This puts us under pressure, which in itself quells a lot of happiness.

335
00:36:46,753 --> 00:36:50,760
So remember that we don't have to feel happy to practice mudita.

336
00:36:51,239 --> 00:36:54,625
The fact that we've taken the time to mark the occasion is enough.

337
00:36:55,505 --> 00:37:01,594
We can keep reminding ourselves of this whenever we feel jealousy, boredom or irritation setting in.

338
00:37:02,266 --> 00:37:03,949
Say we're at a graduation party.

339
00:37:04,469 --> 00:37:12,922
After an hour or so we get fed up hearing about all the courses and exams they passed and wish they had just dropped out after the first day.

340
00:37:12,981 --> 00:37:17,047
Any effort to be happy on their account sets our teeth on edge.

341
00:37:18,050 --> 00:37:20,634
Our practice with the small stuff can't help here.

342
00:37:21,275 --> 00:37:30,889
Although our heart has closed down at the thought of our friend's great achievement, we might still be able to enjoy the food or see the beauty of a flower arrangement

343
00:37:30,869 --> 00:37:35,295
or we might get a little lift by listening to the music that's playing in the background.

344
00:37:37,157 --> 00:37:48,673
Ironically, even our misery can be a basis for mudita, as we say well done to ourselves for every moment we endure in our efforts to celebrate our friend's achievement.

345
00:37:50,697 --> 00:37:56,724
I hope this talk has helped clarify the importance of joy in the spiritual path.

346
00:37:56,992 --> 00:38:04,119
In meditation we have the joy of piti, which results from interest in the process leading to liberation.

347
00:38:05,079 --> 00:38:11,706
It's what keeps us coming back to the cushion, back on retreat, despite all the dukkha we witness there.

348
00:38:12,505 --> 00:38:19,132
In daily life we're sustained by mudita, by the joy that arises naturally when things go well for us.

349
00:38:20,032 --> 00:38:23,876
We cultivate mudita by paying deliberate attention

350
00:38:23,856 --> 00:38:34,253
to anything that makes life pleasant, inspiring or easy and getting into the habit of saying thank you and well done many times every day.

351
00:38:34,293 --> 00:38:46,371
An especially important aspect of mudita is to rejoice in our own good deeds and every attempt we make to practice meditation and incorporate the Dhamma into our lives.

352
00:38:47,143 --> 00:38:54,257
Congratulating ourselves for all these builds up the self-confidence we need to follow the path to liberation.

353
00:38:56,422 --> 00:39:03,938
May our efforts to cultivate mudita bring joy to our lives and to the lives of those we love.

